******
[1] Michigan (Grand Traverse County)
Date: Tue 23 Dec 2014
Source: Mlive [edited]
http://www.mlive.com/news/grand-rapids/index.ssf/2014/12/grand_traverse_reports_81_whoo.html


The whooping cough outbreak in Grand Traverse County has reached 81 cases. Four babies younger than 12 months have been affected, the health department reported on Tue 22 Dec 2014.

An advisory [notice] from the health department regarding pertussis, also called whooping cough, encourages residents to take precautions with holiday travel and get-togethers to prevent the spread of disease. Children and adults are advised be up-to-date on vaccinations, including booster shots for pertussis. And people are urged to stay home if they are sick.

The pertussis outbreak has affected students at 22 schools in the county. The health department also reports 21 cases of parapertussis, an illness similar to pertussis.

A hotline set up to answer questions from those who have been exposed to pertussis has received more than 3900 phone calls. "Preventing severe disease and death in infants is our highest priority," the advisory says. The health department "urges all pregnant women to get vaccinated and parents to vaccinate infants as soon as possible."

Infants who are too young to be vaccinated are the most vulnerable to severe, sometimes fatal, cases of pertussis. The health department says it is important for all those in close contact with newborns and infants to have up-to-date vaccines, an approach called cocooning. Mothers, fathers, siblings, grandparents, aunts, uncles and anyone who might be around an infant during the holidays should be vaccinated, said Wendy Trute, the Grand Traverse health officer.

[byline: Sue Thoms]

