[Grand Traverse County is located in the north west part of Michigan's Lower Peninsula http://en.m.wikipedia.org/wiki/Michigan. The name Michigan is the French form of the Ojibwa word mishigamaa, meaning "large water" or "large lake." Those living in the Upper Peninsula (or UP) are called "Yoopers," now an official word in the Merriam Webster Dictionary. The 2 peninsulas are connected by the famous Mackinaw Bridge, and those of us residing in the lower regions of the state are sometimes referred to by our northern neighbors as "Trolls", as we live underneath the bridge.

In Grand Traverse County, there are a number of reasons why the local outbreak has occurred, including decreased efficacy of the current acellular vaccine (see below), the natural 3-5 year waves of the infection, and a substantial "philosophical" objection rate among parents to the vaccine.

It should be noted that _Bordetella pertussis_'s cousin, _B. parapertussis_, causes a similar, although milder, illness to _B. pertussis_. There is, however, no cross-protection against parapertussis with the pertussis vaccine. Parapertussis does not produce the pertussis toxin. Co-infections with pertussis and parapertussis are not rare. - Mod.LL]

******
[2] Nebraska (Lancaster County)
Date: Fri 26 Dec 2014
Source: KETV [edited]
http://www.ketv.com/news/lincoln-health-officials-seeing-unprecedented-number-of-whooping-cough-cases/30415802


Lincoln-Lancaster County health officials have recorded 110 confirmed cases of whooping cough, and the number is growing.

On Tue 23 Dec 2014, one family in Lincoln learned that their 16-year-old son was one of those afflicted. "The doctor said he's got pertussis or whooping cough," the teenager's father said. That meant even though no one else in the family has it yet, it was home for the holidays. "It is a terrible gift to give, so we don't want to give this to anybody," the mother said. The family even left gifts they were going to take to relatives out on their porch. "They didn't say, 'Hi,' or nothing. They picked it up and drove off," the teenager said.

No one appreciates that more than health officials in Lincoln, faced with all the cases in 2014. "It's the highest we had recorded. The last numbers even close to that were in 2005, and we had 87," supervisor of the Communicable Disease Program Tim Timmons said.

Pertussis outbreaks are occurring all across the country. Health officials said the vaccination apparently wears off. Kids are supposed to get 4 doses of it by age 2, another when they enter grade school, and a booster shot in high school. "The immunity doesn't seem to last as long, maybe 3-4 years," Timmons said. That's why so many middle and high school students, like this teenager, seem to be getting the disease even when they had their shots.

[byline: Andrew Ozaki]

